Customer Churn Prediction

Gyujin Seo

2022-08-07

1 Introduction

1.1 Problem Statement

Churn rate is the number of new customers compared to the number of churning customers. This is important because the cost of acquiring new customers is much greater than the cost of retaining existing ones. Therefore, if existing customers who are likely to churn can be identified and prevented in advance, the effect can be greater than simply acquiring more new customers. In addition, if the customer churn rate is accurately predicted, the customer lifetime value (CLV) and return on marketing investment can also be calculated more accurately, which in turn helps to make the right decision.

1.2 Goal

For the stability of the company’s financial problems, create a model to predict what customer has a high risk of leaving the bank’s credit card services.

3 Data Preprocessing

# Check for duplicate customer numbers
length(unique(data$CLIENTNUM)) == length(data$CLIENTNUM)
## [1] TRUE

There are no duplicate customer numbers

#Combine college, Doctorate, Graduate and Post-Graduate into Degree recipient
data1 <- data
data1$Education_Level <- ifelse(data$Education_Level == 'College' | data$Education_Level == 'Doctorate'| data$Education_Level == 'Graduate'|
data$Education_Level == 'Post-Graduate', 'Degree recipient', data$Education_Level)

data1 <- data1 %>%
    mutate(Attrition_Flag = ifelse(Attrition_Flag == "Attrited Customer", "1", "0"))
data1$Attrition_Flag <- factor(data1$Attrition_Flag)

data2 <- data
data2$Education_Level <- ifelse(data$Education_Level == 'College' | data$Education_Level == 'Doctorate'| data$Education_Level == 'Graduate'|
data$Education_Level == 'Post-Graduate', 'Degree recipient', data$Education_Level)
# Replace 'unkown' values to NA
data2 <- data2 %>%
    mutate(Attrition_Flag = ifelse(Attrition_Flag == "Attrited Customer", "1", "0"),
           Education_Level = ifelse(Education_Level == "Unknown", NA, Education_Level),
           Income_Category = ifelse(Income_Category == "Unknown", NA, Income_Category),

#Arrange Client number

           Education_Level = factor(Education_Level,levels = c("Uneducated","High School", "Degree recipient"),
                                    labels  = c("Uneducated","High_School", "Degree_recipient")),
           Marital_Status = factor(Marital_Status,levels = c("Divorced", "Married", "Single")),
           Card_Category = factor(Card_Category, levels = c("Blue", "Silver", "Gold", "Platinum")),

4 Modeling

#Data partitioning
set.seed(2022)
train_index <- createDataPartition(y = data2_order$Attrition_Flag,  # y = our dependent variable.
                                   p = 0.7,  # Specifies split into 70% & 30%.
                                   list = FALSE,  # Sets results to matrix form.
                                   times = 1)  # Sets number of partitions to create to 1.

train_data <- data2_order[train_index,]  # Use train_index of iris data to create train_data.
test_data <- data2_order[-train_index,]

4.1 Logistic Regression

4.1.1 Stepwise Logistic Regression

set.seed(2022)

fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10, savePredictions = TRUE)
#Logistic regression
Model <- glm(Attrition_Flag ~ ., data = train_data, family = "binomial")
#Logistic regression with stepwise
step_Model <- stepAIC(Model,
                   direction = "both",
                   trace = F,
                  trControl = fitControl)
# Create object of importance of our variables
step_importance <- varImp(step_Model) %>%
    rownames_to_column("Variable") %>%
    arrange(desc(Overall))

# Create plot of importance of variables
ggplot(data = step_importance, mapping = aes(x = Overall,
                                             y = reorder(Variable, Overall))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Variable importance: Stepwise Logistic Regression Model")+
  theme_light()

# Predict
prediction_step <- predict(step_Model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
prediction_step <- prediction_step %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    magrittr::set_colnames(c("prob")) %>%
    mutate(pred_class = ifelse(prob > 0.5, 1, 0))

table(prediction_step$pred_class, test_data$Attrition_Flag) %>% # Create prediction table.
  prop.table() %>% # Convert table values into proportions instead of counts.
  round(2) # Round numbers to 2 significant values.

4.2 LASSO Regression

set.seed(2022)
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10, savePredictions = TRUE)

lasso_model <- train(Attrition_Flag~., data = train_data,
               method = "glmnet",
               tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 1, lambda = seq(0.001, 0.1, by = 0.0002)),
               trControl = fitControl)
lasso_model$bestTune

5. Summary

5.1 ROC curves and AUC values

preds_list <- list(prediction_step$prob, # stepwise
                   prediction_lr[,2], # logistic reg
                   prediction_Lasso[,2], # lasso
                   prediction_dt[,2], # decision tree
                   prediction_rf[,2], # random forest
                   prediction_nb[,2],# prediction_nb,
                   prediction_svm$prob, # svm
                   prediction_knn[,2] # knn
                   )

m <- length(preds_list)
actuals_list <- rep(list(test_data$Attrition_Flag), m)

pred <- prediction(preds_list, actuals_list)
rocs <- performance(pred, "tpr", "fpr")

auc.tmp <- performance(pred,"auc")
auc <- as.numeric(auc.tmp@y.values)

actual <- as.integer(as.character(test_data$Attrition_Flag))
auc_step <- auc[1] %>% round(4)
auc_lr <- auc[2] %>% round(4)
auc_lasso <- auc[3] %>% round(4)
auc_dt <- auc[4] %>% round(4)
auc_rf <- auc[5] %>% round(4)
auc_nb <- auc[6] %>% round(4)
auc_svm <- auc[7] %>% round(4)
auc_knn <- auc[8] %>% round(4)

plot(rocs, col = as.list(1:m), lwd = c(1, 4, 1), main = "ROC curves")
legend(x = "bottomright",
       legend = c(paste0("Stepwise LR (AUC=", auc_step, ")"),
                  paste0("LR (AUC=", auc_lr, ")"),
                  paste0("LASSO (AUC=", auc_lasso, ")"),
                  paste0("Decision Tree (AUC=", auc_dt, ")"),
                  paste0("RF (AUC=", auc_rf, ")"),
                  paste0("Naive Bayes (AUC=", auc_nb, ")"),
                  paste0("SVM (AUC=", auc_svm, ")"),
                  paste0("kNN (AUC=", auc_knn, ")")),
       fill = 1:m)

5.2 Results

This is a summary of all the prediction models that were done. Random Forest has best model compared to other with Kappa, Sensitivity, Specificity and F1 score has shown at least 96% accuracy. Random Forest have AUC score of 98% that shows the model is learning the data well enough.
